; dxgi.def - exact name + ordinal preservation for our proxy dxgi.dll.
;
; What we export: the 20 dxgi-namespace exports captured from the
; current System32 dxgi.dll export set (`dumpbin /exports
; C:\Windows\System32\dxgi.dll`). This covers DXMD's static dxgi
; imports plus middleware (PIX, AMD AGS, etc.) that resolve dxgi
; exports at runtime via GetProcAddress.
;
; What we DO NOT export: any additional dxgi-namespace functions
; that future Windows versions might add as the API evolves. We
; deliberately do not pre-emptively mirror those for two reasons:
;   1. Their signatures would be undocumented. Shipping a stub with
;      a guessed calling convention or argument count is worse than
;      not shipping it — a wrong-shape stub could corrupt the
;      caller's stack on return.
;   2. DXMD shipped in 2016 with middleware from that era. None of
;      it uses post-2016 dxgi additions.
; A caller that imports a dxgi export we don't expose will see
; GetProcAddress return NULL through our proxy (where it would
; have succeeded against real System32 dxgi). For DXMD this never
; happens. For arbitrary other apps that try to use our DLL as a
; general-purpose dxgi proxy (which is NOT a supported use case),
; some calls would fail. See README's compatibility-matrix section.
;
; Ordinals here match the captured System32 dxgi exactly so any
; caller resolving by ordinal still gets the right function through
; our proxy (verified to match across our test installs).
;
; On older Windows (Win7 SP1 / Win 8.1) some of these 20 exports may
; be missing from the host's System32 dxgi entirely; for those
; slots, the per-export pfn_FOO stays pointing at its compile-time
; trap (see SECTION 1 of src/dxmd_thread_fix.cpp). That degrades a missing-export call
; to a typed failure return rather than a crash.
;
; Why preserve ordinals (and not just names)?
;   - Most callers (DXMD included) resolve dxgi exports by NAME via
;     the IAT, so name preservation alone would suffice for them.
;   - But some graphics tooling and a few less-common libraries do
;     resolve by ORDINAL (especially the older D3D10-era code paths
;     like DXGID3D10CreateDevice). For those, the ordinal must match.
;   - Matching both is the conservative choice — costs us nothing,
;     buys us compatibility with the long tail.
;
; Each export's implementation is the same-named symbol in dxgi_stubs.asm,
; which tail-jumps to the runtime-resolved real-dxgi pointer in SECTION 6 of
; dxmd_thread_fix.cpp. See docs/DESIGN.md for the full proxy-DLL story.

LIBRARY dxgi
EXPORTS
    ApplyCompatResolutionQuirking      @1
    CompatString                       @2
    CompatValue                        @3
    DXGIDumpJournal                    @4
    PIXBeginCapture                    @5
    PIXEndCapture                      @6
    PIXGetCaptureState                 @7
    SetAppCompatStringPointer          @8
    UpdateHMDEmulationStatus           @9
    CreateDXGIFactory                  @10
    CreateDXGIFactory1                 @11
    CreateDXGIFactory2                 @12
    DXGID3D10CreateDevice              @13
    DXGID3D10CreateLayeredDevice       @14
    DXGID3D10GetLayeredDeviceSize      @15
    DXGID3D10RegisterLayers            @16
    DXGIDeclareAdapterRemovalSupport   @17
    DXGIDisableVBlankVirtualization    @18
    DXGIGetDebugInterface1             @19
    DXGIReportAdapterConfiguration     @20
